<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congressman's Widow Seeks His Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) -- The widow of 18-term Democratic  
Rep. George E. Brown is fighting nine contenders for her husband's 
seat in a race that's seen as an early test of the GOP's ability to 
hold on to or expand its majority in the House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Marta Macias Brown faces a major challenge from a Democratic  
state senator in addition to her Republican opponent in the special 
election Tuesday to represent the district at the inland edge of 
Los Angeles' sprawl. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42nd District, former home of Kaiser Steel, has blue-collar  
roots and a Democratic edge in voter registration, but party 
allegiance isn't strong. Brown, who died in July at age 79, was on 
the GOP's hit list for years. Typical of off-year elections, the 
race is stirring less interest in the district than in Washington, 
where a fight over gun control is seen as a possible preview of 
next year's house elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``To some extent, it's a testing of the waters for both  
parties,'' said Michael LeMay, a political science professor at 
California State University, San Bernardino. 
</P>
<P>
	With 10 candidates, it is considered unlikely that anybody on a  
ballot this crowded can pull 50 percent of the vote to avoid a Nov. 
16 runoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown, 54 and a longtime advocate for Hispanic issues who  
worked on her husband's staff, is concentrating her campaign 
against fellow Democrat Joe Baca, a moderate state senator from 
Rialto. Also running is another Democrat with name recognition in 
the district, Fontana Mayor David Eshleman. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrying the GOP's hopes to build on the party's 222 to 211 seat  
majority in the House is businessman Elia Pirozzi, who lost to 
Brown by a 15 percent margin last year. Also on the ballot are two 
other Democrats, two Republicans, including Rob Guzman who withdrew 
from the race, and two minor-party candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who was serving his 18th term in Congress when he died,  
was a liberal and longtime booster of science spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In a campaign waged mostly by personal appearance, mail and  
radio advertising, the national issue to emerge has been a fight 
over gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown is a staunch advocate of banning assault weapons and  
cheap handguns, and has accused Baca, who has been supported in 
past campaigns by the California Rifle and Pistol Association, an 
affiliate of the NRA, as soft on an issue gaining momentum in the 
state after the Jewish center shootings in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Her direct mail campaign has attacked Baca as ``the radical gun  
lobby's favorite Democrat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baca responded with a mailer that pictured him standing next to  
Democratic Gov. Gray Davis as the governor signed a bill requiring 
that guns be sold with trigger locks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be there gun control on every issue. But I  
will be on common sense legislation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	An August poll by the liberal women's group Emily's List found  
Baca leading with 22 percent, Pirozzi with 17 percent and Brown 
with 16 percent. When respondents were told the candidates' 
positions on gun control, the field reversed: Brown 32 percent, 
Baca and Pirozzi 15 percent. The poll, conducted by Fairbank, 
Maslin, Maullin &AMP; Associates, has a 4 to 5 percent margin of error. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
