<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jimenez Leads Lancome Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAINT-NOM LA-BRETECHE, France (AP) -- Defending champion Miguel  
Angel Jimenez still has the lead, but now it's just one stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimenez shot a 1-under par 70 Saturday and leads Pierre Fulke by  
one shot entering the final round of the $1.29 million Lancome 
Trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Fulke, who entered the round six shots off the lead,  
finished with a 6-under par 65. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last big event before next week's Ryder Cup, Jimenez  
finished the third-round at 11-under par for a total of 202. 
</P>
<P>
	European No. 1 Colin Montgomerie is at 9-under with a 204, with  
Sweden's Ryder Cup player Jarmo Sandelin and Spain's Ignacio 
Garrido three shots off the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimenez, who secured the Lancome Trophy last year with a  
brilliant chip on the last hole, had a three-stroke lead over 
England's Gary Evans entering the third round. 
</P>
<P>
	And he gave every indication that he would retain the title with  
birdies on the third and eighth holes, at which point he had a 
five-stroke lead. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 35-year-old Spaniard missed a six-foot putt for par on  
the 10th and Fulke began to make his move. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing conditions were nearly perfect, with warm, bright  
weather and a slight breeze drying out the damp greens that had 
caused problems for some golfers over the first two days. 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomerie started at six-under, four behind Jimenez.  
</P>
<P>
	He birdied the first hole, but a bogey on the fourth set him  
back in his chase for a 23rd European circuit win and second at the 
Lancome event. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Van de Velde, who like Jimenez and Sandelin will appear in  
the Ryder Cup for the first time next week, was playing in front of 
French fans for the first time since losing a three-stroke lead on 
the last hole at the British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 33-year-old couldn't maintain the solid form that had  
put him 4-under par after the first two rounds. He quickly dropped 
out of contention with a succession of early bogeys. 
</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde recovered to make par, and he ended the day seven  
shots behind Jimenez. 
</P>
<P>
	Scotland's Andrew Coltart, who will play in Brookline after  
getting a surprise wild card, missed the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	After his round, Montgomerie said that Jimenez would likely pair  
up with fellow Spaniard Jose Maria Olazabal, who has struggled 
recently, during the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will be a very good combination,'' Montgomerie said.  
``(Olazabal) is obviously concerned about his form but I think he 
will play all five,'' Montgomerie said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ryder Cup is about more than golf and if it came down to a  
four or five-foot putt to win then he is the player you or I or the 
rest of the team would vote for to hole it,'' Montgomerie added. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryder Cup captain Mark James also backed Olazabal, who was  
four-under par after Saturday's third round. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every player's form is a concern. I have 12 players and there  
was every chance that some would be playing well and some wouldn't 
be,'' James said. ``I'm not particularly worried about anyone at 
this stage and by all accounts Olazabal has been playing well this 
week.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
