<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Newspaper Editor Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- The editor-in-chief of a major independent  
newspaper was arrested Saturday for alleged financial corruption at 
the daily, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Riyad Hroub, editor-in-chief of al Arab al Yawm, was denied bail  
and will remain in detention for 14 days pending interrogation, the 
officials said on customary condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at al Arab al Yawm declined to comment and no further  
information on the arrest was immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Hroub has been engaged in a running feud with the authorities  
over the newspaper's critical reports and cynical commentaries 
about the government. Authorities have temporarily cut off the 
service of the state news agency for the newspaper, accusing it of 
``unethical reporting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hroub has also been fighting several lawsuits filed by some of  
his staff following numerous layoffs at the newspaper, which is 
said to be facing serious financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Khalid Zubeidi, a board member at the National House for  
Publishing and Distribution, which publishes the newspaper, also 
filed a lawsuit against Hroub last month, accusing him of 
``financial mismanagement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al Arab al Yawm, one of the most prominent of Jordan's six  
dailies, is an independent newspaper with a circulation of 70,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
