<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Leaguer Suspended for Tipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Huntsville Stars catcher Jeff Alfano was  
suspended for tipping off Orlando batters to upcoming pitches in an 
extra inning game that may have affected the Southern League 
championship scenario. 
</P>
<P>
	The Milwaukee Brewers, the Stars' parent club, suspended Alfano  
for 30 days and fined him $500, to be donated to a charity 
designated by the major league team, according to Milwaukee 
director of player development Cecil Cooper. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huntsville Times reported Cooper's action Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	The punishment follows investigations by the Brewers and the  
Class AA Southern League. It will take affect at the start of next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Cooper said Alfano admitted telling Orlando Rays  
batters what pitches were going to be delivered in an extra inning 
game on Sept. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy did it out of frustration is the way I've had it  
explained to me,'' Cooper told The Times in a story Friday. ``He 
apologized to his teammates and he apologized to me. I think he has 
shown a lot of remorse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alfano did not return calls from the newspaper. He did not have  
a listed number in Huntsville. Officials with the Stars did not 
immediately return a call from The Associated Press on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlando eventually won the game in 17 innings, finishing in a  
tie with Jacksonville for the Southern League East second half 
title. Orlando went on to beat Jacksonville in a one-game playoff 
and advance to the championship series against West Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfano, a 23-year-old from California, had served a six-game  
suspension in August after tearing apart the Huntsville clubhouse 
buffet in a postgame rampage after being criticized by manager 
Darrell Evans. 
</P>
<P>
	Stars president and general manager Don Mincher said if anything  
the latest punishment was too light. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfano's actions ``affected the outcome of a game in a negative  
way, and that's a very, very serious infraction,'' Mincher told the 
newspaper. ``The integrity of the game has got to be protected. 
This not only affects our club, but the whole league. ... I think 
he did a disservice to baseball.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
