<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Die in Pakistan Train Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAXILA, Pakistan (AP) -- A passenger train slammed into a lone  
engine traveling in the other direction Saturday night, killing at 
least 18 people and injuring 70 others, witnesses and railway 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear what caused the crash or why the  
two trains were on the same stretch of track a few miles outside 
Taxila, 21 miles from the capital, Islamabad. 
</P>
<P>
	The first railway car of the six-car passenger train, the Chenab  
Express, was a mangled mass of steel and the second one was badly 
damaged. The death toll was expected to climb as many of the 
wounded were in serious condition, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Railway officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said the  
engine apparently accidentally rolled out of the Taxila station 
along the tracks until it smashed into the oncoming passenger 
train, which was heading toward the Arabian Sea port city of 
Karachi. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Wah Military Hospital, where many of the wounded were  
taken, Mohammed Aurengzeb cradled his wife's head in his hands. She 
was unconscious. 
</P>
<P>
	``I woke up with the crash and I began to look for my wife,'' he  
said. ``I didn't know what had happened. I yelled her name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Awakened by the sound of the accident, nearby residents ran from  
their homes to the crash site, removing the dead and wounded, 
flagging down cars, trucks and horse-drawn carts to take the 
injured to nearby hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	The last major train crash was in March 1997 when a runaway  
train jumped its tracks and slammed into a sand dune in the eastern 
Punjab province, killing 135 people and injuring 175 others. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past decade, more than 2,000 people have died in train  
crashes in Pakistan. The deadliest crash occurred in 1989 when two 
passenger trains slammed into each other in southern Sindh province 
killing 850 people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
