<HEADLINE> Train Crash Cuts Sewage Tanker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GALISTEO, N.M. (AP) -- A Los Angeles-bound passenger train sliced  
into a truck hauling sewage, splattering blue, disinfectant-laden 
liquid onto the train, but leaving the truck driver with only minor 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The tank ``just spewed like a balloon,'' sending 300 gallons of  
blue-tinted liquid and toilet paper into the air, said Santa Fe 
County sheriff's Deputy Joe McLaughlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Lorenzo Mendoza, 35, of Pecos, was treated at St. Vincent  
Hospital in Santa Fe after Friday afternoon's accident at a rural 
crossing on County Road 42. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's lucky it hit the back of the truck,'' McLaughlin said.  
</P>
<P>
	The accident delayed the Chicago-to-California Southwest Super  
Chief and its 160 or so passengers for 1 1/2 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators had not determined whether Mendoza saw the train  
or tried to speed across the tracks ahead of it. There are no 
traffic barriers or flashing lights at the crossing. 
  	   	
