<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indexes, Stocks Not on Same Page </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If your favorite stocks lagged this past month  
while the Dow Jones industrials and the Nasdaq composite index 
soared to new records, you're not alone. 
</P>
<P>
	For several months, a relative handful of stocks have driven  
market indexes higher while the vast majority of issues turned in 
middling-to-poor performances. Many analysts, particularly the 
technical strategists who gauge the market's strength by crunching 
numbers, fear that all is not well beneath the lofty levels of most 
indicators. 
</P>
<P>
	``The broader market has not been participating,'' said Brian G.  
Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in 
Kansas City, Mo. ``There are a number of signs that not all the 
planets are aligned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow offers perhaps the clearest illustration of the market's  
lack of consistency. The average of 30 blue-chip stocks is up 17.7 
percent so far this year, slightly ahead of its 16.1 percent gain 
in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But the performances are widely divergent among the stocks that  
comprise the Dow. Computer maker Hewlett Packard is up 47.6 percent 
for the year to date, while retailer Sears, Roebuck has plunged 
20.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 has been similarly unbalanced. So far  
in 1999, the top 15 stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 have accounted for 70 
percent of the total gain in the index, said James M. Griffin Jr., 
chief investment strategist at Aeltus Investment Management in 
Hartford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the market's bad breadth developed as a few prized  
stocks -- mostly technology companies like Microsoft, Intel and 
Cisco Systems -- continued their runaway growth while fears of 
rising interest rates and inflation began depressing the broader 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Performance this year has been concentrated in the same tech  
names we love to love if we own them and love to hate if we 
don't,'' Griffin said. 
</P>
<P>
	To illustrate the market's narrow advance, analysts point to the  
New York Stock Exchange's advance-decline line, a ratio that 
compares the number of stocks that rise in any given session to the 
number of stocks that fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The advance-decline line peaked in April 1998, when the strong  
U.S. economy lured many buyers into the market. By this summer, 
however, declining stocks outnumbered advancers in nearly every 
session. That held true even on days when the Dow posted 100-point 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	That worries analysts, because it suggests that investors lack  
confidence in the broad market. With only a handful of stocks 
leading the market, one bad break in the form of a poor earnings 
report or leadership change can send market averages plummeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stock market history tells us that narrow markets can endure  
for a long time, but eventually they develop into a problem for 
investors,'' said John A. Mendelson, of Schwab Capital Markets &AMP; 
Trading Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffin said the narrow market may be especially vulnerable in  
the face of rising interest rates. The Federal Reserve has already 
raised rates twice since June in a bid to stem inflation, and may 
do so again if policy-makers determine that higher rates would hold 
the nation's economic growth to sustainable levels. The Fed's next 
meeting is Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	While keeping inflation under wraps is important to investors,  
higher rates could also leave many traders with less money to pour 
into the stock market. In addition, rising rates hurt stocks by 
increasing a company's borrowing costs, and by boosting the returns 
available on other investments, such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the money becomes less abundant, you have to choose your  
favorites,'' Griffin said. ``You can drive stocks up at a slower 
rate, but some will undoubtedly fall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP;  
Sons Inc., has noted the sluggish performance of most stocks, yet 
remains optimistic about the market's underlying strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is still a bull market,'' Goldman argued. ``The stock  
market is supported by solid fundamentals with a healthy economy, 
low inflation, low interest rates and strong corporate earnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His advice? ``In a selective market, be selective.''  
</P>
<P>
	This past week, the Dow ended 224.80 points lower. A gain of  
66.17 Friday left the blue-chip index at 10,803.63. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq fell 17.44 over the course of the week. The index  
gained 62.90 on Friday to close at 2,869.62. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index lost 16.24 for the week, rising  
16.94 Friday to close at 1,335.42. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index, which reflects the performance of  
small-company stocks, lost 6.74 for the week, closing at 434.45 
after gaining 4.20 Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, which represents the  
combined market value of all NYSE, American and Nasdaq issues, 
ended the week at $12.183 trillion, off $164.66 billion from last 
week. A year ago, the index was $9.361 trillion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
