<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 02:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey Towns Battle Floyd Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOUND BROOK, N.J. (AP) -- It happened so fast that people didn't  
have time to take pets, or even shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	Muddy water from the Floyd-swollen Raritan River raced through  
this low-lying town and others near it early Friday, engulfing 
homes to their top floors, killing two people, leaving fires raging 
for hours in downtown buildings and forcing nearly 2,000 to leave 
by boat or helicopter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were literally picking people off the rooftops,'' said  
Denise Coyle, the director of the Somerset County Board of 
Freeholders. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three deaths were blamed on the flooding in the state,  
including a 75-year-old woman and her 50-year-old son who refused 
to let police evacuate them, Gov. Christie Whitman said. 
</P>
<P>
	A 2 1/2-year-old boy found waist-deep in floodwater, crying alone  
near a car, was reunited with his parents Friday afternoon after 
police took him to a nearby hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never seen anything like this,'' said Whitman, who  
announced that President Clinton had declared an emergency 
situation in New Jersey because of the flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Bound Brook, located about 35 miles west of New York  
City, was the New Jersey area worst hit by Floyd-related flooding, 
it wasn't the only one. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as a million people in Essex, Morris, Passaic, Somerset,  
and Union counties were told to boil their water, at least through 
the weekend, after floodwaters overwhelmed the Elizabethtown Water 
Co.'s main water treatment plant in Bridgewater. 
</P>
<P>
	About 140,300 homes and business remained without electric  
service early today. Utility officials estimated that more than 
100,000 customers would not have their power restored until Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The floods curtailed long-distance phone service to nearly 1  
million people, mostly in Passaic and Bergen counties, and knocked 
out all service to another 35,000. It even prevented some ATM and 
credit card transactions -- across the nation -- because a key 
telephone switching center in Rochelle Park flooded. 
</P>
<P>
	The floodwaters receded Friday in Bound Brook. Authorities  
prepared search teams to enter 200 waterlogged homes to look for 
anyone who may still be inside today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now it looks like a big mudslide,'' Somerset County emergency  
management director LeRoy Gunzelman said this morning. ``The 
water's gone, and there's mud and debris all over the roads. The 
structures have to be tested today to see if they're even safe 
enough for the search and rescue team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The flood shocked and devastated even those who were veterans of  
many floods in those low-lying communities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's happened to them so many times,'' said Karen  
Fritz of Bound Brook. ``We figured the water would go down. The 
water never went down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The scenario was familiar to Mary Straub, 67. She lost her home  
to a flood in 1971 and rebuilt it in the same spot. Authorities 
said it may be days before she is allowed to see the damage of this 
storm. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very devastating, really,'' Straub said while sitting a  
high school converted into a temporary shelter. ``You can't believe 
it's going to happen to you a second time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
