<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Seizes Frankel Estate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service has seized  
an estate owned by Martin Frankel, the financier accused of bilking 
insurance companies out of hundreds of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, who has been in custody since his Sept. 4 arrest in  
Germany, owned two estates in Greenwich. The first, a 4-acre 
property valued at $3 million, was taken by the FBI in May on 
allegations it served as headquarters for Frankel's money 
laundering and investment fraud enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS expropriated the second estate, valued at $2.5 million,  
alleging it was bought with money that had been wired from the same 
Swiss bank account into which Frankel deposited $44 million of the 
stolen insurance funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The seizure order, based on a complaint by the IRS's Criminal  
Investigations Division, was signed Sept. 10 by U.S. District Judge 
Dominic J. Squatrito in New Haven. 
</P>
<P>
	Copies of the order have been sent to Frankel's former  
bodyguard, David Rosse, and a former Greenwich landlord, Cheryl 
Lacoff, who both have claims against the property. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosse and Lacoff have until next week to file notice of intent  
to litigate with the government to recoup money from Frankel 
through the IRS's eventual sale of the property. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
