<HEADLINE> Kasparaitis May Leave U.S. To Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Darius Kasparaitis, discouraged by the slow  
movement of contract talks with the Pittsburgh Penguins, plans to 
leave for Switzerland on Monday to train with Ottawa Senators 
holdout Alexei Yashin. 
</P>
<P>
	Both players are represented by agent Mark Gandler.  
</P>
<P>
	Kasparaitis, a defenseman recovering from reconstructive knee  
surgery, said he and the Penguins are about $300,000 apart in 
yearly salary, but that he has been making all the concessions. The 
Penguins' initial offer was $1.2 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's frustrating. It's killing me,'' Kasparaitis said. ``I'm  
trying to keep my head up and I want to come back to Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins general manager Craig Patrick suggested the team won't  
make a new offer any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've extended ourselves as far as we're going to extend  
ourselves,'' Patrick said. ``I don't know if there is a line in the 
sand, but we've made a substantial offer, by our estimation. 
Obviously, not by theirs. And that's as far as we can go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasparaitis, who has been working out on his own in New York, is  
the Penguins' last remaining restricted free agent who has not 
reached terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, $300,000 isn't that big of a deal,'' Kasparaitis  
said. ``But I'm the only one who keeps going down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Kasparaitis isn't threatening to stage a long holdout like  
Petr Nedved, who stayed out for 17 months before the Penguins 
traded him to the New York Rangers in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not Petr Nedved,'' Kasparaitis said. ``Petr's a single  
guy. My wife's got to go shopping. I hope to get this down soon.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
