<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: GOP Tax Plan Hurts Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Renewing his veto threat, President Clinton  
said Saturday that the Republicans' 10-year, $792 billion tax cut 
plan would result in ``some of the worst cuts in education in our 
history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the nation's 31 Republican governors joined with  
GOP congressional leaders in promoting their tax package. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Republicans send me a bill that doesn't live up to our  
national commitment to education, I won't hesitate to veto it,'' 
the president said in his weekly radio address. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on behalf of Republicans, Gov. Jim Geringer of Wyoming  
argued for a massive tax cut funded though projected budget 
surpluses over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why not give the money and our government back to the  
people?'' Geringer said in the GOP's radio address. ``He accused 
Clinton of seeking to ``spend every spare dollar of the surplus ... 
and obligate more of your family's income for the next 10 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. J.C. Watts, chairman of the House Republican Conference,  
also issued a statement touting the GOP's plan for education 
improvements. Watts, R-Okla, said they will allow control of 
education to remain with parents and teachers and not ``some 
clock-puncher in the massive Department of Education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republican tax-relief package meets America's priorities  
by making crucial investments in education,'' Watts said, citing 
proposed expansion of pre-paid tuition plans and expansion of 
tax-free savings accounts for education. 
</P>
<P>
	Watts called Clinton's remarks ``a last-ditch effort to spin the  
American people out of their desire for real tax relief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton contended the Republican proposal would shortchange  
the nation's school children and their future workplace success as 
they begin ``the last school semester of the 20th century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Using part of a projected 10-year surplus, the Republican tax  
bill would reduce all income tax rates by 1 percentage point; cut 
capital gains taxes; gradually eliminate estate taxes and the 
alternative minimum tax; ease the ``marriage penalty'' paid by many 
two-income couples; expand pension laws; and give breaks for 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton contends it would draw away money needed to preserve  
Medicare and Social Security and to ensure adequate spending on 
education and defense. Tax cuts, he says, should be targeted at the 
middle class and come only after those priorities are met. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the Republican proposals would require cuts in  
federal aid to education of more than 50 percent over the decade 
and force a 20 percent reduction next year alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``If carried out this plan would lead to some of the worst cuts  
in education in our history,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton asserted that a cut of that size would possibly lead  
next year to laying off 5,000 of the new teachers hired under his 
class-size reduction initiative, eliminate after-school and 
summer-school programs for 50,000 students and reduce chances for 
future success for more than 10 million students in the nation's 
poorest communities. 
</P>
<P>
	He then made his threat to veto a GOP education bill explicit.  
</P>
<P>
	``If it undermines our efforts to hire high quality teachers to  
reduce class size or increase accountability in our public schools, 
I'll veto it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it fails to strengthen head start, after-school, and summer  
school programs, I'll veto it. If it underfunds mentoring or 
college scholarship programs, I'll veto it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If it sends me a bill that turns its back on our children and  
their future, I'll send them back to the drawing board,'' Clinton 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
