<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Rookie Debuts With Tampa Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Tampa Bay's Jim Morris, a 35-year-old  
left-hander, became the oldest rookie in the majors in 29 years 
when he struck out Royce Clayton in the eighth inning of Saturday 
night's 6-1 loss to Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris relieved with two outs and struck out Royce Clayton on  
four fastballs in the mid-90s. 
</P>
<P>
	He is the oldest rookie since 36-year-old Minnie Mendoza with  
Minnesota in 1970 and the oldest rookie pitcher since 41-year-old 
Diomedes Oliva with Pittsburgh in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like my heart was going to jump out of my chest,''  
Morris said. ``It was an unbelievable experience. It made me feel 
young. I recommend it for anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, who had a large contingent of family and friends in the  
stands, said he had little control when he was warming up in the 
bullpen in the eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was everywhere in the bullpen,'' he said. ``I was just  
trying to keep my heart from exploding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he was told his fastball registered in the mid-90s, Morris  
said, ``To tell you the truth, I never can tell how hard I'm 
throwing. I'm just trying to get guys out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris was given the ball that was in play at the time as a  
keepsake. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild had said before the game he  
did not want Morris to make his major league debut on the day he 
was called up, but Rothschild then decided to put in Morris right 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came in and got the out,'' Rothschild said. ``He threw hard  
and looked like he was putting the ball where he wanted it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, a native of Brownwood, Texas, was teaching chemistry and  
physics at Regan County High School in West Texas about 3 1/2 months 
ago when he was given a tryout by the Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, taken by Milwaukee with the fourth overall pick the 1983  
amateur draft, went 3-1 in 18 relief appearances at Triple-A Durham 
of the International League. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays also brought Julio Franco back to the major  
leagues when they purchased the contract of the 14-year veteran 
from Durham. 
</P>
<P>
	Franco, 38, signed with Tampa Bay in spring training and was  
assigned to the Devil Rays' affiliate in the Mexican League, the 
Mexico City Tigers. Franco led the Mexican League with a .423 
average and a .656 slugging percentage, then hit .269 in seven 
playoff games for Durham. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay also called up first baseman Steve Cox from Durham and  
activated right-hander Cory Lidle from the 60-day disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room, Tampa Bay designated outfielders Rich Butler and  
Carlos Mendoza, right-hander Mickey Callaway and left-hander 
Terrell Wade for assignment. The Devil Rays have 10 days to trade 
them, place them on unconditional release waivers or assign them 
outright to the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay also said Durham manager Bill Evers will be with the  
major league club as a coach for the rest of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
