Braves 4-3 Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux (18-8) has lost consecutive starts after winning eight in  
a row. He allowed eight hits, struck out eight and walked one in 
his fourth complete game of the season, the 92nd of his career. His 
ERA, which had been 5.02 on May 21, dropped to 3.35. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta, seeking its eighth straight division title, began the  
night two games ahead of second-place New York in the NL East. The 
Braves have lost five of seven. 
</P>
<P>
	Hermanson (9-12) allowed all three runs and 11 hits in eight  
innings, struck out five and walked two. Ugueth Urbina pitched the 
ninth for his 38th save in 46 chances. 
</P>
<P>
	Two errors by second baseman Bret Boone and one by Maddux did in  
the Braves, who led 3-1 with two outs and none on in the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Bergeron singled and Jose Vidro hit a slow grounder up the  
first-base line. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux failed to pick up the ball on his first attempt, then  
tried a back-handed, overhead toss that first baseman Ryan Klesko 
could not handle. Bergeron advanced to third on the error and Vidro 
wound up on second. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir Guerrero followed with an RBI single, and Fullmer's  
double down the first-base line put Montreal ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone's 20th homer and Ryan Klesko's RBI double put the Braves  
ahead 2-0 in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	Vidro reached on an infield single in the fourth and advanced on  
a throwing error by Boone. One out later, Boone made another bad 
throw on Fullmer's grounder, allowing Vidro to take third. He 
scored on Michael Barrett's grounder. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone hit an RBI single in the bottom half.  
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Braves will top 3 million Sunday, the third straight  
year they've topped the mark and the fifth time in the 1990s. 
Saturday's sellout was the 19th of the season. ... Since his July 
15 recall from Triple-A Ottawa, Fullmer is hitting .323 
(66-for-204) with six homers, 21 doubles and 35 RBIs. 
  	   	
