<HEADLINE> Senate Said Eyeing NFL Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The chairman of the Senate's Caucus on  
International Narcotics Control reportedly has begun an inquiry 
into how the NFL handled the cases of 16 players who failed drug 
tests in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported Sunday that Sen. Charles E. Grassley  
of Iowa has requested a copy of a videotape made at an NFL Players 
Association meeting four years ago. During that meeting, Doug 
Allen, the union's assistant executive director, said a number of 
players were not punished for violating the league's substance 
abuse policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL later confirmed that 16 players were not suspended as a  
concession to the union during negotiations on a stronger 
drug-testing policy. Those players, however, continued to be 
monitored and tested under the new policy. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Times, Grassley sent a letter to Sportsolution,  
which shot the videotapes, saying: 
</P>
<P>
	``How the United States deals with drug abuse and addiction  
domestically reflects on our efforts and credibility in the 
international arena. No group -- especially one with such high 
visibility as the players of the National Football League -- should 
be allowed to hide drug use behind negotiations or posturing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the tapes reveals what I fear they do, the public deserves  
to know.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
