<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Boss Stays Out of Sanders Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue is not expected  
to get involved in talks to get Barry Sanders to end his retirement 
now that his dispute with the Detroit Lions is headed for 
arbitration, the running back's agent said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	David Ware said he had spoken to Tagliabue before the Lions  
filed papers to have a portion of Sanders' signing bonus returned. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commissioner was very understanding and empathetic but  
indicated that he would not get involved in terms of a dispute 
between the Lions and Barry, but he would welcome the opportunity 
to welcome Barry to return,'' Ware said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamont Smith, Sanders' other agent, asked Tagliabue in a letter  
Monday to help settle the Lions' grievance against Sanders, aimed 
at recouping $5.6 million of the signing bonus the Lions contend 
Sanders owes them. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware said since Tagliabue does not get involved in these kinds  
of disputes, an arbitrator will be appointed. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the question of whether Sanders owes the Lions any money  
is discussed, the arbitrator would have to decide on a number of 
procedural issues -- one being the timeliness of the filing of the 
grievance by the Lions, Ware said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter Friday to the NFL Management Council, Smith argued  
that the Lions waived their right to file a grievance because they 
didn't do it within 45 days of Sanders' failure to report for a 
mandatory minicamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could decide that Barry owes the Lions nothing or he could  
decide that Barry owes them something between the amount $7 million 
and $5 1/2 million roughly,'' Ware said. ``I think this case could go 
either way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Lions spokesman Bill Keenist declined to discuss  
any of the latest developments. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to comment on anything other than to state  
again that we respected Barry's wishes to retire and have proceeded 
accordingly since,'' Keenist said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who needs only 1,458 yards to break Walter Payton's  
career rushing record, disputes Detroit's claim that he is required 
to repay a portion of the bonus if he doesn't play. 
</P>
<P>
	An NFL spokesman also confirmed Saturday that Tagliabue told  
Ware on Sept. 2 that he was willing to talk with Sanders if it 
would help the running back return to the Lions, but not if he 
wanted to play for another team. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commissioner said he would be willing to talk to Barry if  
it would be constructive, but he didn't want to get between Barry 
and the Lions,'' said Greg Aiello, NFL vice president of public 
relations. ``He called (Lions vice chairman) Bill Ford and told him 
about the conversation and never heard back from David Ware or the 
Lions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aiello said an arbitrator has yet to be appointed, nor has there  
been a date set to hear the Lions' grievance -- a proceeding he said 
might not happen for ``four to six months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is still unknown whether the 31-year-old Sanders wants to  
play again. Ware said last week that Sanders was ``ready to 
consider it, in the right situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like for him to play tomorrow. But that's Barry's call,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ware and Smith said Sanders should be granted free agency or  
traded if he repaid $5.6 million of his $11 million signing bonus, 
which the Lions contend represented the unfulfilled portion of the 
six-year contract he signed in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Lions received the payback, they could use the money  
against the salary cap for other players. The Lions have said they 
have no interest in releasing or trading Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have your money back, why should you still have the  
right to dictate where he works,'' Ware asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders did not collect a $1.7 million deferred payment due this  
fall on the original bonus. He also forfeited his 1999 base salary 
of $3.125 million and a reporting bonus of $250,000 by leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue said at an Economic Club luncheon in Detroit last  
month that the Lions had not asked for salary cap relief in the 
case and that the NFL would not grant it if they did ask. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to work this out. We remain committed to working  
this out for the best interest of the Lions, Barry and the NFL,'' 
Ware said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
