<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crews Search for the Stranded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Rescue teams in boats and helicopters set  
out again today to hunt for people marooned by the worst North 
Carolina flooding in decades, as people up and down the East Coast 
dealt with the damage left by Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	A Navy helicopter roared overhead this morning as dozens of  
people walked and rode bicycles to downtown Tarboro to watch the 
Tar River crest about 24 feet above its 19-foot flood stage. The 
bloated river lapped at businesses three blocks from the riverbank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen anything like this in my life,'' said Maryann  
Harris, who owns three downtown businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 1,500 people remained stranded today, some on roofs  
or in trees, across a broad swath of the eastern half of the state. 
In Edgecombe County alone, about 3,500 people had been rescued by 
today, said Kenny Johnson, a county emergency management official. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 38 people died -- including 13 in North Carolina -- when  
Floyd churned up the East Coast. Thousands of homes and businesses 
were damaged and nearly a million people were without electricity. 
The much weakened storm sped through Maine on Friday and entered 
the Bay of Fundy off Nova Scotia in late evening. 
</P>
<P>
	In Bound Brook, N.J., serious flooding from the Raritan River  
forced police to rescue more than 1,000 people Friday, many of them 
from second-floor windows or off porch roofs. Nearly 8,000 people 
spent Friday night in emergency shelters in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never seen anything like this,'' New Jersey Gov.  
Christie Whitman said. President Clinton declared an emergency in 
the state, allocating federal funding to help deal with the 
cleanup. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 4,000 people were left homeless by flooding in  
southeastern Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Some North Carolina rivers swollen by rain from Hurricane Floyd  
earlier in the week approached flood levels not seen for 70 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jim Hunt appealed for use of all private helicopters in the  
western part of the state, and additional helicopters were due 
today from Texas, Florida and Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Professional rescuers were joined by neighbors in motorboats.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is neighbor rescuing neighbor in a lot of situations out  
there,'' said North Carolina emergency management spokeswoman Renee 
Hoffman. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way we have a firm number to the number of people  
who are waiting. We assign a flight to pick up a certain number of 
people and they find others along the way. This is a 
find-people-as-you-find-them situation,'' Ms. Hoffman said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,000 people sought refuge Friday night in 86 shelters in  
eastern North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Several rivers including the Tar, Neuse, Cape Fear and Roanoke  
were expected to crest near record levels in the next several days 
as they inundated entire towns, the National Weather Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm that came ashore early Thursday dumped 15 inches of  
rain on the state's coastal plain. Coming on top of an 8-inch 
rainfall from Hurricane Dennis less than two weeks earlier, the 
effect was devastating. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're looking at is flooding of historic proportions,''  
said state meteorologist Ron Wall. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of Interstates 95 and 40, the state's busiest highways,  
remained closed by high water and about 250 roads were listed as 
impassable across the eastern third of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in New Hanover County and Wilmington, where Floyd  
dumped at least 15 inches of rain, said Friday the storm destroyed 
160 homes and caused nearly $24 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200,000 customers in North Carolina remained without  
electricity. Late Friday, the entire city of Greenville and its 
48,000 electric customers went black when the rising Tar River 
short-circuited a critical transmission station. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, more than 65,000 customers remained without power  
Friday night in Pennsylvania; 145,000 in New Jersey; 35,000 in 
Vermont; 200,000 in Maryland, 95,000 in Virginia and 80,000 in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	In Virginia, more than 118,000 people in Portsmouth and parts of  
Chesapeake and Suffolk had no drinking water because a pumping 
station was flooded. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Lynn Schum of Lima, Ohio, had been stranded at a Holiday  
Inn in Jacksonville, N.C., for three days after she and nine others 
were evacuated from their vacation cottage at Topsail Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tomorrow, it's either Topsail or home -- come hell or high  
water,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
