<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bias Case Costs Transit Agency $5M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A state transit agency has been ordered to pay  
$5.5 million to a black employee who was subjected to years of 
pranks and racial slurs by supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority foreman Hiram  
Clifton, 49, was awarded $500,000 for emotional pain and suffering 
and $5 million in punitive damages, the Boston Globe reported 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	MBTA officials said they would appeal the Suffolk Superior Court  
jury's verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Clifton, who worked at the agency's Charlestown equipment yard,  
said his white supervisors fired bottle rockets at him, wrote 
racial slurs on his locker, squeezed toothpaste on his lunch, and 
routinely addressed him with profanity and derisive nicknames. 
</P>
<P>
	He still works for the MBTA, but in a different area.  
</P>
<P>
	The verdict is the latest blow against the MBTA, which has been  
assailed by charges of racism and sexism in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	MBTA officials acknowledged that civil rights complaints have  
been unusually high at times at the 6,500 member organization. But 
Diane Wong, the MBTA's head of organizational diversity, said new 
anti-discrimination policies are working. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
