<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Asst. Coach Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama assistant basketball coach  
Robert ``Rah'' Scott will begin chemotherapy treatment this week 
after being diagnosed with stomach cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``My family and I know that God is on our side as we attempt  
this fight,'' the 41-year-old Scott said in a statement released by 
the university. ``I have always been a strong and determined 
individual. I'm looking upon this with none other than a positive 
attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama coach Mark Gottfried said Scott will continue to be a  
part of the coaching staff as long as his health permits. He said 
Scott ``is more than a co-worker, he's one of my best friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he's a fighter,'' said Gottfried, who brought the  
former Alabama star back as part of his staff last year. ``I'm 
going to support him and pray for him, and we'll celebrate when he 
beats it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Birmingham, Scott was a two-time captain at Alabama  
in 1979 and 1980. After playing overseas for six years, he served 
as a high school coach before becoming an assistant coach at UAB in 
1996. He returned to Alabama in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott is the second Alabama assistant coach to battle cancer.  
Kermit Koenig, an assistant under former coach David Hobbs, was 
diagnosed with cancer during his first season. Koenig currently 
works with the basketball's Tide Pride program. 
</P>
<P>
	Gottfried said assistant Philip Pearson would take Scott's place  
on recruiting trips, but said he did not anticipate any staff 
changes this season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
