<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 17:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres 11, Giants 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Damian Jackson and Quilvio Veras each homered  
and drove in three runs to lead the San Diego Padres over the San 
Francisco Giants 11-5 Saturday, stopping the Giants' six-game 
winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco dropped seven games behind NL West-leading  
Arizona, which beat Florida 8-6 in 10 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson hit a sacrifice fly in the second and had a two-run  
homer off Mark Gardner (4-11) in the fourth that gave San Diego a 
4-1 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Veras homered leading off the first to tie the score and added a  
two-run single in a seven-run sixth that made it 11-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Sterling Hitchcock (12-12) allowed one run and four hits in six  
innings, getting 13 outs on grounders. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Gwynn was 2-for-4 to raise his career hits total to 3,051  
and needs two to tie Rod Carew for 18th on the career list. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner, making his first start since Aug. 28, pitched in place  
of Livan Hernandez, who has a strained rib cage. Gardner gave up 
four runs and five hits in four innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Bonds hit his 32nd homer in the first inning, raising his  
career total to 443 and moving past Dave Kingman into 22nd place on 
the career list. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego sent 13 batters to the plate during the sixth, which  
included a three-run double by Wally Joyner, and RBI singles by 
Gwynn and Phil Nevin. San Francisco helped with a walk, two hit 
batters and an error. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco added three runs in the seventh against Carlos  
Reyes on pinch-hitter Jay Canizaro's two-run homer and Charlie 
Hayes' RBI double. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Bonds has hit 50 career home runs against San Diego, more  
than he has against any other team. ... Veras' leadoff homer was 
the sixth of his career. ... Ellis Burks was back in San 
Francisco's starting lineup after missing two games because of sore 
knees. ... The Padres won for just the 22nd time in 65 games 
against teams with winning records. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
