<DOCNO> APW19990918.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 13:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUDON, N.H. (AP) -- Jeff Burton has said all along that too much  
emphasis is placed on qualifying for Winston Cup races, and that 
starting far back in the field does not drastically reduce the 
chances of a top finish. 
</P>
<P>
	And he proved that two months ago at New Hampshire International  
Speedway, when he started 38th yet won the Jiffy Lube 300 for the 
third straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	So, defeatism won't be part of his package when he straps  
himself into his Ford and starts 37th Sunday in the Dura Lube 300. 
But he's getting tired of not knowing why he struggles so much in 
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real frustrating, because when you think you're starting  
to learn something you haven't learned a thing,'' said Burton, 
whose three career NHIS victories and five overall this year match 
the circuit-best numbers of Jeff Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton has been thrilling plenty of fans with his back-to-front  
dashes when he qualifies poorly. But he doesn't want to keep doing 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton's fate is far better than that of three-time series  
champion Darrell Waltrip, who failed to make the field for the 
third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Others who failed to qualify were Derrike Cope, Dick Trickle and  
Andy Belmont. Making the field on owner points were Burton, Kenny 
Wallace, Brett Bodine, Chad Little, Dave Marcis, Rich Bickle and 
Jimmy Spencer. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	BAD TIMES: Auto racing is like the legitimate stage in many  
ways, where regardless of circumstances the show usually goes on. 
Still, drivers are not oblivious to tragedy that strikes others and 
the danger they encounter each time they race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be lying to you if I told you I didn't think about it for  
a moment,'' Kenny Wallace said in discussing the death Sept. 11 in 
Monterey, Calif., of CART rookie Gonzalo Rodriguez. ``I think as a 
race car driver you think about it and then purposely get it out of 
your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No driver can afford -- nor do they have the idle time -- to be  
preoccupied during a race. But Wallace says they accept tragedies 
as inevitable in motorsports. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know the risks out there,'' he said. ``That's why we  
all hope for the best and prepare for the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the drivers don't dwell on it in discussions with one  
another. 
</P>
<P>
	``When there's a death in racing, basically it's a short-witted  
conversation like what happened and how we can prevent it,'' 
Wallace said. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	PIT STOPS: Jeff Gordon's unsuccessful run at a record-tying  
third straight Winston Cup title was short-circuited long ago by 
poor finishes. But when he's been on, it's been vintage Gordon. 
Although he's sixth in the series standings, no one has led more 
races, laps or miles. ... A victory by Dave Marcis would be the 
first from the 43rd -- and now last -- spot on the grid since Fonty 
Flock came from that far back in the field to win in Raleigh, N.C., 
in 1953. ... Seven-time Winston Cup champion Dale Earnhardt has 
completed 2,692 of a possible 2,700 laps in nine previous New 
Hampshire races. ... Gordon's victory last August in the CMT 300 is 
the only one by a polesitter on the picturesque New England track. 
... Rusty Wallace won the first New Hampshire race after starting 
33rd on the grid in 1993. ... Two-time series champion Terry 
Labonte makes his 628th consecutive start, extending his own NASCAR 
record for perseverance. ... Wallace won the inaugural Loudon event 
in a Pontiac in 1993. The only Pontiacs to finish among the top 
five since were those of John Andretti last year and Bobby Hamilton 
in 1997. ... Shawn Parker, a crew member for Mark Martin, has been 
fined $5,000 for pulling an official out of the way while NASCAR 
was detaining the Ford on pit road on Sept. 11 in Richmond, Va. ... 
Ken Schrader is thinking about his two children as he contemplates 
his new ride next year with MB2 Motorsports. ``What could be better 
than Daddy having a sponsor that gives them free M&AMP;M's,'' Schrader 
said. ... Presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole will be the grand 
marshal Sunday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
