<HEADLINE> Pickens Back As Starter for Bengals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Carl Pickens is the Cincinnati Bengals' career  
leader in receptions and touchdown catches. So it's only natural 
that Pickens -- fresh from signing a five-year contract -- is a 
starter again. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is Carl's team,'' wide receiver Willie Jackson said. ``I  
realize that. He's making all the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson started last Sunday in the Bengals' season opener at  
Tennessee, after Pickens ended a holdout by signing a contract only 
two days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson caught five passes for 60 yards in the 36-35 loss. It  
was his best day since catching a career-high eight passes for 69 
yards in 1996 while playing for the Jacksonville Jaguars in 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickens, a Pro Bowl receiver with the Bengals after the 1995 and  
`96 seasons, signed a five-year, $23.25 million deal Sept. 11 -- 
after he threatened to skip the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickens saw limited action last weekend against the Titans.  
</P>
<P>
	Jackson is in the final year of a two-year contract he signed  
with Cincinnati as a free agent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals plan to keep using Jackson often.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just have to be ready to make a play,'' Jackson said. ``The  
more you play, the better you keep playing. I haven't had a lot of 
opportunities to be an every down player, but I know I can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bengals rookie quarterback Akili Smith, embarrassed about his  
lack of production last week when inserted after starter Jeff Blake 
had to leave the game with cramps, has been studying the playbook 
harder this week. Blake will start Sunday against San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from trying to play better his next time out, Smith hopes  
to look good if he is called upon to play against San Diego, the 
team from his hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a Chargers fan in the winning seasons and the losing  
seasons,'' said Smith, a San Diego native. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 6 years old when his Bengals mentor, offensive  
coordinator Ken Anderson, directed the Bengals to a victory over 
the Chargers in the January 1982 AFC championship game in 
Cincinnati. The game was dubbed the ``Freeze Bowl'' because it was 
played in bitterly cold weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he would love a chance to play against the Chargers.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be real strange because I grew up watching those  
games and now I'm watching on the other side,'' Smith said. ``If I 
get the opportunity to play, I want a good showing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
