<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced for Kennedy Hoax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A man convicted of selling forged documents  
supposedly written by John F. Kennedy was sentenced to 10 years and 
three months in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge called Lawrence X. Cusack III a ``man without  
scruples who would sacrifice any person or institution in the 
service of his greed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Denise Cote also ordered him to repay  
investors who sunk $7 million into the bogus stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Given an opportunity to speak before sentencing, a visibly  
flustered Cusack declined as he took off his glasses and rubbed his 
hands over his eyes. One of his lawyers handed him a tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	Cusack, 48, of Fairfield, Conn., was convicted in April of 13  
mail and wire fraud charges alleging he cheated investors of about 
$7 million between 1993 and 1997 with his false claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the false stories were claims that the president had set  
up a trust for Marilyn Monroe's mother to buy silence about their 
rumored affair and bogus proof that the president had covered up a 
secret marriage and divorce prior to his marriage to Jacqueline 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents nearly led to a chapter in Seymour Hersh's book,  
``The Dark Side of Camelot'' -- until their authenticity was 
challenged and the Pulitzer Prize-winning author deleted the 
chapter prior to publication. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors proved that one letter purportedly signed by Kennedy  
included zip codes that did not exist in the early 1960s and 
another that used a typeface created in the 1970s. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
