<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 18:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd-Spurred Floods Recede in N.J. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOUND BROOK, N.J. (AP) -- Record flooding caused by Hurricane  
Floyd's torrential rain receded Saturday, leaving a layer of 
reddish mud and residents anxious to return to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Several streets remained closed in the Raritan River town and  
National Guardsmen barred residents from returning to their homes, 
saying building inspectors needed to make sure it was safe to enter 
the buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Christie Whitman toured shelters in Somerset, Bergen,  
Passaic counties, saying she expects the damage to top $100 
million. The governor also got an earful from angry evacuees in 
Lodi who demanded to know when they could return home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll do everything we can,'' Whitman said. ``Unfortunately,  
it won't be easy and it won't be quick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some 300 people remained in shelters in Lodi.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in these clothes since Thursday,'' said Charnett  
Hillireo. ``I have a 4-year-old here. He's going nuts. He didn't 
fall asleep till 4 a.m. He just keeps crying, `Mommy, I want to go 
home.' Who's going to help us?'' 
</P>
<P>
	State Police said a 75-year-old woman and her son, 50, were  
found dead in their flooded home in Bound Brook. New Jersey had a 
third death, at Little Falls, but officers did not have details. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service said the Raritan River crested at a  
record 14 feet above flood stage at Bound Brook and Manville. It 
was more than 4 feet above the record levels of Tropical Storm 
Doria in 1971 and a February flood in 1896. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton on Saturday declared eight New Jersey counties  
federal disaster areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Bound Brook police said a curfew would be set for the flood area  
to stop people from returning to potentially unsafe homes and to 
prevent looting. The curfew was to last from 7 p.m. Saturday to 7 
a.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	About 74,000 New Jersey homes and business remained without  
electricity Saturday night. Utility officials estimated that 
service would be restored to most of those customers by Sunday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 500,000 customers of Elizabethtown Water Co. were told to  
boil their water, because the company's treatment plant in 
Bridgewater was flooded and company officials feared it might be 
contaminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Powers, 40, stood outside the house he and his wife  
had moved into in May, grateful that the mortgage company insisted 
they buy flood insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the time I groused, but now that the basement is flooded,  
for $700 I can't complain,'' Powers said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990918.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-18 14:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bahamians Reflect on Hurricane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- The waitress smiles, but fatigue circles  
her eyes. While serving customers in a Nassau cafe, Erica Wilson's 
mind wanders to family she hasn't been able to contact since 
Hurricane Floyd hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking a break on her Saturday morning shift, Wilson said she is  
concerned about relatives on Grand Bahama whose phones have been 
down since Floyd battered the island with 150-mph winds. 
</P>
<P>
	She is also weary because Floyd's handiwork has left her without  
water and electricity for five days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't even flush the toilet,'' Wilson said. ``I get up in  
the dark, and have to have my clothes ready for this morning shift. 
``I've got two kids. Imagine that, with no water and no 
electricity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Power has been restored to about 80 percent of New Providence  
Island, home to the capital of Nassau and half the country's 
310,000 people. However, residents were still scrambling for clean 
drinking water and ice to fill coolers used as temporary 
refrigerators. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Bahamians are just grateful that so few people were killed  
or injured here before the storm moved on to the United States. 
Only one confirmed death in the Bahamas has been blamed on 
Hurricane Floyd -- a Nassau woman who was electrocuted Thursday when 
power was restored to her home. A man on Grand Bahama was swept to 
sea during the storm Tuesday and is missing and feared dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the worst affected islands -- Abaco, Cat, San Salvador  
and Eleuthera -- are still largely without electricity and phone 
service. Businesses and the government have begun shuttling water, 
food and plastic tarps to those islands. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is still tallying the number of lost homes and  
surveying other damage in this 700-island archipelago. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents who haven't had electricity since Monday gathered on a  
public dock to drink and talk. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing else to do,'' said Gregory Neely, 26, with a  
beer bottle in one hand and an unopened one in the other. ``It 
isn't all that bad. We just have to rough it for now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Audrey Grant, 12, didn't mind though. ``We get a day off from  
school,'' she said. ``What could be better than that?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
